✨Bettering your sleep schedule
✨Finding joyful ways to move your body
✨Unpacking your body image story
✨Eating a variety of foods that make you feel good
✨Addressing your mental health
✨Starting a stress-relieving routine
✨Setting boundaries with friends and loved ones
✨Building new social connections
✨Restoring your relationship with food

What would life look like if you shifted your focus from shrinking the size of your body to working on behavior changes to not only improve your health but your quality of life? ⤵️

DOUBLE TAP THIS POST IF YOU ARE CURIOUS ABOUT REMOVING PHYSICAL AND MENTAL RESTRICTION WITH FOOD! 

Let’s unpack this. 

Think 🤔about foods that diet culture says are “good” and you should be eating  like chicken, spinach salad, brown rice, veggies, or fruit… 🥗

You become sooooooo f*cking used to eating these food, that you would never want to binge on them.  You aren’t AFRAID to eat chicken and spinach salad. But then what foods did you find yourself craving?  Carbs, ice cream, sweets, and treats? 🍨 H*ll yes. 

Now think about a time when you went on a vacation and enjoyed wayyyy more play foods like chocolate, alcohol, and pizza… When you got home, what did you crave?  You probably craved a vegetable or something that wasn’t as available on the trip.  You’re body may be screaming for fiber so you can finally take a good sh*t 💩

The more you eat a food… the more exposure you have to it… the more normal it becomes. This is the beauty of food habituation and making peace with food in your intuitive eating journey. 

You might be feeling worried that you’ll never stop eating the play foods like pizza and cookies, but we hope you don't stop eating them!  We hope you are able to enjoy them and see them as JUST food. 

Making peace with food allows you to stop FEARING the food. You stop feeling like you’re going to binge on forbidden foods because you know they are always available. 

This is how you STOP the physical and mental restriction. 

Give yourself unconditional permission to eat by making peace with ALL food.

⁉️Have you ever wondered what’s affecting your SETPOINT⁉️

Without any ✨external interference✨ our bodies will RESPECT your unique setpoint range. 

But what are external interferences?

Anything related to dieting: 
❌Intentional restriction
❌Counting calories
❌Cutting out food groups
❌ Restricting the times you can eat 

If we could just listen to our body’s cues and not make choices based on intentionally shrinking our body there there would be less interference.

Setpoint is a delicate balance of homeostasis. Our bodies want to be in homeostasis.  It ONLY works if we let it! 

What are a few things you do to STOP the interference? 
☑️Listen to your body’s hunger and fullness cues
☑️Respect your body 
☑️Make peace with food 
☑️Ditch dieting for good 
☑️Find satisfaction in your eating experience 

Today we welcome you to work WITH your body, not against it.💙

The carnivore diet’s secret is OUT! 

People see quick “results” when they cut those carbs.  But we say, give me all the carbs, anyway.🍞 

So what’s the “weight loss secret” of the carnivore diet? 

It’s simple.  Carbs retain more water 💧 per gram than protein does. 

So when we remove carbs, we drop water weight. 

There is nothing 💫magical 💫 about the carnivore diet. 

That water weight loss is the flame of diet culture that feels exciting and lures you f*cking in. 

But it’s temporary.  It’s not sustainable.  And it’s definitely not healthy physically, mentally, and emotionally.

Removing carbs doesn’t teach you anything.  It doesn’t improve your relationship with food.  It might cause you WAY more stress in the long run. 

Today we welcome you to explore your relationship with carbs.  Is removing them helpful or harmful?  We hope you discover that carbs are f*cking delicious and an amazing part of gentle nutrition.

Our baby is 1 today🥹🥲

After a morning full of snuggles, singing, dancing, and birthday balloons…we dropped her off at daycare and I got myself my favorite coffee order (venti oat milk iced latte with sweet vanilla cold foam DUH💁🏼‍♀️) and headed straight to the beach to enjoy my morning coffee☀️

I used to go out to the beach a lot during our years of infertility. I would sometimes walk and sometimes sit and play music that gave me hope. I would cry. I would cry hard. I would sit there and know that even though the pain and deep ache in my heart felt so permanent that one day our miracle would arrive🌈

And today that little miracle is one year old. I sat on the beach, played the same music that I used to cry/pray to, and soaked in the moment. I feel so grateful to be her mom. I feel so grateful to raise a human being. I feel so grateful to watch her grow into her true authentic self and be a safe space for her.

If you are in a dark season right now, whether that be with infertility or your relationship with food and body image or maybe something completely different…please know that it is a season. Your feelings are valid. It’s okay to not be okay AND it will get better🫶🏼

My morning on the beach reminded me that THIS is what food freedom is all about. I was able to be 100% present and soaked in so much gratitude and joy. It felt so so so good. This is why I do what I do, so other humans can stop the food and body obsession and enjoy the beauty that is happening all around them✨

Thanks for reading my ramble.

So much love for you,

Sam

So give yourself the time and space to work on the body image work spectrum.

That is a f*cking cool part of food freedom. 

So what can you do to support your relationship with food when your sick and feeling sh*tty? 
✨Consider a zinc supplement.  Zinc is a well-researched mineral!  It’s so important for your immune health.  When you feel sickness coming on, it can support your immune system.  Having Zycam on hand can be helpful. Always read the labels and talk to your
✨Take a multivitamin.  Multivitamins can help fill in any nutrition gaps, especially if your appetite is off when you are sick or if you are having changes in taste, preferences, and cravings. 

It takes privilege to buy these supplements, but if you’re able, these are two simple ways to get in some vitamins and minerals when you feel that sickness coming on.  Please note that this is for educational purposes only and not medical advice.  Always talk to your doctor and dietitian about supplements to figure out which ones are right for you.

Whatever energy you can put into your body when sick, that is all that matters 💙

Humans have emotions. Humans need to eat.

Emotional eating is a normal human experience.

Food has always provided us with some level of comfort throughout our lives. But it’s important to dive into these and recognize the “why” behind your emotional eating ⤵️

▪️ Were you taught to rely on food to handle negative emotions/situations as a child?
▪️ Do you eat emotionally because it makes you feel better at that given moment?
▪️ Do you eat emotionally because it’s an easy, accessible coping mechanism?
▪️ Do you associate emotional eating with instant relief from your stress and or/emotions?

Whatever your “why” is, recognize that emotional eating has served a purpose in your life - and you are not a bad human being for experiencing this💙

Food is always available if you need it, but pinpointing other coping mechanisms will help you satisfy your physical, emotional, and mental well-being in the long-run.

Have you heard about set point theory, or “set point weight?”

The basic idea is this: Our bodies don’t like change. Your body likes to maintain homeostasis (remember that term from high school science class?).

That means it regulates itself so that your biological systems mostly stay within set ranges. Our bodies do not like drastic changes or fluctuations, so they work to keep everything at an even level.

😱 A big increase or decrease in your blood pressure?
🌡️ A big drop or spike in your body temperature?
❤️ Your heart’s suddenly racing or way too slow?

These things typically signal that something is wrong. Maybe it shouldn’t surprise us that this includes our weight.

Set point theory says that our bodies each have a certain weight range - largely determined by genetics - that they like to maintain… in spite of our best efforts.

When you go on a diet to force yourself below your set point range.. this sets off alarm bells🔔 in your body, and it responds by doing everything it can to stop you from losing weight: it slows down your metabolism, decreases your fullness cues, and increases your hunger cues.

This is all in an effort to keep you alive, because your body doesn’t know the difference between a diet and starvation on a deserted island.

While diet culture may look at set point theory as a new angle for weight loss (with promises like “trick your body - reset your set point!“), understanding set point weight and what it means for your health can actually be very liberating and empowering on your intuitive eating journey.🙌

Embracing the fact that your body can regulate itself plays a huge role in learning to trust your body so that you can let go of strict rules and restrictions around food.💙

BUT - it’s also very scary to trust your body in the face of all the diet culture noise insisting that we need to trick, reset, hack, or control our bodies to be “healthy.”

We get it! ⬇️
